        <section>
            <h>complement</h>
            <p><g>ceàrr</g> can take a complement, introduced by the preposition <a href="?gd=air"><g>air</g></a> <en>on</en>.</p>
            <p>Some examples –
            <xl>
                <li>
                    <gd>Dé tha <m>ceàrr air a’ ghille seo</m>? Tha a cheann goirt.</gd>
                    <tr>What is wrong with this boy? His head is sore.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                </li>
            </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>
    
    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section id="uses-predicate">
            <h>predicate</h>
            <p>Like other adjectives, <g>ceàrr</g> can be used (uninflected) as the predicate of the
                verb <a href="?gd=bi"><g>bi</g></a>.</p>
            <p>Some examples – <xl>
                <li>
                    <gd>Dé tha <m>ceàrr</m> air a’ ghille seo? Tha a cheann goirt.</gd>
                    <tr>What is wrong with this boy? His head is sore.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                </li>
            </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="uses-mod">
            <h>modifier</h>
            <p>Like other adjectives, <g>beag</g> can be used to modify a <a href="?xx=nouns/nouns"
                >noun</a>.</p>
            <p>Some examples with masculine nouns – <xl>
                <li>
                    <gd>Tha an <m>cat beag</m> bàn aig an teine.</gd>
                    <tr>The little white cat is by the fire.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 9</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <gd>Càit a bheil an <m>gille beag</m> an diugh?</gd>
                    <tr>Where is the little boy today?</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                </li>
            </xl>
            </p>
            <p>When the modified noun is feminine, <g>beag</g> is lenited to <g>bheag</g> – <xl>
                <li>
                    <gd>Tha <m>Màiri bheag</m> sgìth.</gd>
                    <tr>Little Mary is tired.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 9</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <gd>Chan eil a’ <m>chaileag bheag</m> anns an sgoil.</gd>
                    <tr>The little girl is not in the school.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td 14 [228]</ref>
                </li>
            </xl>
            </p>
            <p>Note the difference in meaning between the following examples – <xl>
                <li>
                    <gd>Tha Màiri beag bàn.</gd>
                    <tr>Mary is small and fair-haired.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 8</ref>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <gd>Tha Màiri bheag bàn.</gd>
                    <tr>Little Mary is fair-haired.</tr>
                    <ref text="617">td. 8</ref>
                </li>
            </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
        
